Anonymous Sat 05 Nov 2022 22:13:29 No.52135869 Report
Quoted By: >>52142914
>>52135356
Just the opposite for me. Tanks are cool and all, and I can appreciate how technical the play can be, but it's not really my thing. But planes, especially piston engine warbirds, is something else entirely. Turn battles, pounce and bounce, playing into the strengths of your machine, the mind game. It was all great. Even the weird stuff, like getting used to the painfully low muzzle velocity and insanely high rate of fire of the high tier Russian cannons. Or just hopping into a lemon simply because you know it'll draw idiots looking for an easy kill. Or flying someone out of the sky when you're out of ammo. But my favorite is what I used to call the wounded bird routine. Because air battles are kinda broken and haven't seen love in years, it was always a useful tactic for players to loiter over their airfield, gaining altitude, protected by their insane laser AA. So you'd sniff around and bait the flak, then pop aerobatic smoke (white, center) to simulate a cooling system failure and pretend to limp back to base. Lower throttle to let them catch up, droop your wing if you really want to sell it. Very reliable in drawing them out, and pretty dangerous, because you're still drawing someone with an energy advantage on your six. But you can sense the panic on the other side of that dodgy, Russian internet when you punch the throttle, turn off the smoke, and now they're in a turn fight with what they thought was an easy target.

Haven't played it in years, kind of because the tank battles started getting all the love and Air RB essentially never got out of beta.
